messages.text:
<!channel> Hey gang! Just concluded all of the check ins for the week...if you received a call from a 573 number, that me -- give me a call back. I want to make sure anyone who is still looking has a great gameplan for each week. A lot can change in a week...you can go from nothing to having a job in that short amount of time, and I want to help! A few notes from the calls:

A few of us are working on getting our social profiles updated...this is great! Please shoot over any variations of your website, resume, cover letter, Linkedin links, etc and I can review them with you on a case by case basis.

^^Having said this...DONT let this be what holds you back from applying, networking, etc. I know that you all have heard me preach about LinkedIn and networking through LinkedIn a million times, but this will be your 2nd best tool when helping you find a job. What's the first, you ask? Your network! PLEASE PLEASE PLEASE reach out to me if you see a company that may be of interest to you. I will ping the Galvanize network to see if we have an in for you so we can bypass the dreaded online application black hole (I still recommend that you submit your resume anyway...but we can always use our connections to surface yours to the top!)

Next - In terms of contracting/freelancing: If you are doing contract work, freelance work, or any developing for a company - please let me know ASAP! I will then send over a form that records that you are doing work while we are looking to find you a full time job.
*why this is important:* We want to give you credit for the work you are doing! Documenting that you are working on contract work is important for us to understand what you are doing during your job search - it tells more of a story that you are keeping your skills sharp and working on real life problems, rather than just sitting around playing Xbox and not doing anything to progress your career.
*what this means for you* If you are someone who falls into this bucket, I will proceed to ask a bit more information: What youre doing, how long the project is, etc. If we determine it is something to record through Talent, we will send you form that records this
*WAIT...what if I'm working on a contract but I still want a full time job??* Not a problem! If we end up recording your contract work, you still receive access to ALL that Galvanize has to offer for your 6 months post graduation. You are still a priority for us to help find a full time opportunity. You will still be bugged by me calling/slacking to see how things are going for you.
*Why I think this is the most important* When companies reach out to me, often times they want someone who has kept their skills sharp in an organize, real life environment as well. We get to use this as leverage to value who you are, and what you are doing.

*Please slack me any questions that you may have and we can chat about it on a case by case basis*

As always, office hours are available: <https://calendar.google.com/calendar/selfsched?sstoken=UURZZEJpS25MS3RFfGRlZmF1bHR8NzMxOGJjNzEzNjYwNmQ2NjVkMGQyZTNlOWEzNDk4OGY>

If you havent already, check out the LinkedIn article the career services team here at Galvanize put together: <https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/career-coaches-discuss-what-toughest-obstacles-landing-mukai-matsiga>

attachments.title: Here’s Gollum Singing “Time After Time” Because Why The Heck Not | Nerdist
attachments.text: Smeagol. Cyndi Lauper. Since time immemorial, these two icons of pop culture have stood apart from one another — but today, they have finally combine forces for the mash-up we've all been demanding. Okay, okay! I'll stop fooling around. In all seriousness, this new video by viral YouTube sensation Ian Walters is simultaneously the most grotesque and the most gorgeous "Time After Time" cover I've ever heard. You'd think a centuries-old Stoorish hobbit would lose his ear for harmony after being twisted and corrupted by the One Ring Of Power, but you'd be wrong. Guess being stuck in a cave talking to yourself is a wonderful way to keep your vocal pipes in good health. Like almost everything on the internet, this breathtakingly hilarious video was created to promote a Kickstarter project: Walters is currently attempting to fund his first full-length album under the moniker "Headphone Hair." As of this writing, he only has a few thousand more dollars to raise with ten more days to go. And

<!group> This one should be a quick one. Practice your Polya skills - 

Even Integer Output: Generate a single random number, from 0 to 100, then output all the even integers from 0 to the random number.

Practice Polya’s Method of problem solving:
* Understand the problem  - What are the inputs/outputs?
* Devise a plan - come up with 2 possible solutions.
* Carry out the plan - choose a solution and implement it.
* Look back - test your plan, revise, refactor.

Their typical practice is to hire you as a contractor for 90 days and if everything works out you get to go into employee status after that. Awesome example on how to deliver a message in about 2 minutes: <https://www.ted.com/talks/derek_sivers_weird_or_just_different>

notes for the group: 

Come up with a story! practice it in the mirror on your breaks or in front of someone and ask for candid feedback - this is how we engage and retain the attention of the listeners - 

Make sure not to wrap up with “…and thats all it does” or “and thats about it” because the work you all put into this project is more than “just” anything! Brag about the project - wrap it up with “this is what I set out to do and I’m proud that I accomplished it” type ending. 

Project to the group…not to your screen: Its easy to keep our heads down and just talk while we are going through the project, but make sure we are projecting while we are presenting

Have fun and be you: That’s what really makes these presentations special. Make sure that these projects are a great representation of the you! Why was the project so important to you (back to the story), throw in some humor or anything that eases the tension 

Prepare for anything: Make sure you have something to fall back on if the project doesnt perform as expected, make sure youre prepared to talk even if there is a blank screen behind you. Prepare with a video if that is easier for you as well -

attachments.title: Amazon AWS S3 outage is breaking things for a lot of websites and apps
attachments.text:
Amazon’s S3 web-based storage service is experiencing widespread issues, leading to service that’s either partially or fully broken on websites, apps and devices upon which it relies. The AWS offering provides hosting for images for a lot of sites, and also hosts entire websites, and app backends including Nest.
The S3 outage is due to “high error rates with S3 in US-EAST-1,” according to Amazon’s AWS service health dashboard, which is where the company also says it’s working on “remediating the issue,” without initially revealing any further details.
Affected websites and services include Quora, newsletter provider Sailthru, Business Insider, Giphy, image hosting at a number of publisher websites, filesharing in Slack, and many more. Connected lightbulbs, thermostats and other IoT hardware is also being impacted, with many unable to control these devices as a result of the outage.


Suddenly glad a boarding pass automatically printed when I checked my bag. #s3outage 
— Ted Han (@knowtheory) February 28, 2017

Amazon S3 is used by around 148,213 websites, and 121,761 unique domains, according to data tracked by SimilarTech, and its popularity as a content host concentrates specifically in the U.S. It’s used by 0.8 percent of the top 1 million websites, which is actually quite a bit smaller than CloudFlare, which is used by 6.2 percent of the top 1 million websites globally – and yet it’s still having this much of an effect.
Amazingly, even the status indicators on the AWS service status page rely on S3 for storage of its health marker graphics, hence why the site is still showing all services green despite obvious evidence to the contrary.


The dashboard not changing color is related to S3 issue.  See the banner at the top of the dashboard for updates.
— Amazon Web Services (@awscloud) February 28, 2017

We’re monitoring the situation and will provide more info as it becomes available.
Update (11:40 AM PT): AWS has fixed the issues with its own dashboard at least – it’ll now accurately reflect service status as it continues to attempt to fix the problem.
Update (11:57 AM PT): AWS says it believes they new “understand root cause” of the S3 issues, and are “working hard at repairing.” It has not shared specifics of that cause.
Update (12:15 PM PT): Network intelligence software provider ThousandEyes notes that all the packet loss for the ongoing issue appears to be happening in the Ashburn, VA area. Amazon has an AWS data center in Ashburn, whose exact location was revealed in a news story last year due to a fire during its construction.
Developing…

- *While these aren’t *technically* real interviews with Zayo, you should treat them as such!* They are most definitely looking to Galvanize students for near-future hiring and are seeking to build themselves a list of potentials, while also giving you all great practice.
- *While these aren’t *technically* required, they should be!*  I know you’re working on your capstones, but this will be 15-20 minutes of direct employer feedback. Pretty sure y’all came here to get jobs. :wink:

Honestly this is one of the best times you’ll get to hear someone else give answers that are awesome (or not) and help yourself to evaluate your own answers and questions — while also helping out a cohortmate. Better here than in the real world for reals! I will review and send out final confirmations this evening. YAY INTERVIEWS!

attachments.title: Galvanize - Web Development Resident (WDR) - Boulder - Brown
attachments.text: THIS POSITION IS RESERVED FOR FORMER STUDENTS AND GRADUATES OF GALVANIZE IMMERSIVE PROGRAMS Being a Web Developer-in-Residence (WDR), you would be here at Galvanize Full Time (40 hours per week). The idea is to solidify your new skills through helping students in the classroom as well as going through the curriculum again. In addition, you'd have a chance to really build out your passion project in the intensely creative and talented eco-system here at Galvanize! Your classroom responsibilities will mostly include ‘being on the floor’ which means helping students through the daily exercises. Other classroom responsibilities include reviewing new student applications, interviewing prospective students, building new / iterating current curriculum, grading student tests, and reviewing student code. Your off-time can be devoted to your personal project(s) is designed to give you time to solidify your full stack developer skills, explore passion projects, ramp up your portfolio, and contribute to the Galvanize learning experience in a positive way. As part of the Residency program, you will receive dedicated mentorship from our expert instructors and faculty to cultivate your development as a web developer. It is a 12-week appointment. There is a possible extension an additional 12 weeks depending on staffing needs. WDR contracts will work with Solo Weeks, which will include helping students with their personal and capstone projects as needed. WDRs will be compensated for these weeks as part of the 12-week appointment. San Francisco & Seattle Rates: For 40-hours of work/ week, the stipend is approximately $1,500/ week for 12- week appointment. **(Approximate because stipend depending on actual days worked.) Austin & Colorado Rates: For 40-hours of work/ week, the stipend is approximately $1,250/ week for 12-week appointment. **(Approximate because stipend depending on actual days worked.) We are looking for 1 Resident per cohort depending on staffing needs.

attachments.title: Component and CSS Library Choices for Angular 2
attachments.text:
So you’re ready to take the plunge and develop your next project in Angular 2.  Great!  But, Angular 2 is just one piece of a larger puzzle.  A key question you must answer as you define your Angular 2 architecture, is “which component and styling libraries should be used?”.
Choices
Here is list of choices that this post discusses (in alphabetic order).  For a list from the Angular team itself see .
Angular Material 2
Basecss
Bootstrap (with two flavors of Angular adapters)
Electron
Foundation (not available until late 2016)
Ionic 2
Kendo
NativeScript
PrimeNG
React Native
Tachyons
Wijmo
Wow.  That’s big list, and it’s not exhaustive!
New Angular Features
You may have wrestled with this question while using Angular 1.  Be aware of some important changes with Angular 2.
Renderers
A key new feature of Angular 2 is the separation of the renderer from Angular.  While the most common approach is to use Angular 2 with a browser (and the DOM), you can now use Angular to present native components with tools such as React Native and NativeScript.
Components and View Encapsulation
One of the first things you’ll learn about Angular 2, is that the UI is made from a dynamic hierarchy of components.  View Encapsulation allows you to decide if CSS scope should be local or global. Here’s an article to introduce you to the subject: .
Cordova
Cordova allows you to package your Angular app assets into an app that installs like a native app.  Instead of reading the HTML and JavaScript from a server, it reads from your installed resources.  Plugins allow you to access native features like your camera, GPS, etc.
Some toolkits, like Ionic and Meteor, include Cordova and further automates the packaging process and adds goodies like “live code reload” so when your app changes the new JavaScript and HTML are pushed automatically (in development and production mode).
Considerations
Devices being Targeted
The biggest and most obvious factor is what devices you want to run on. Some choices are mobile only, some are web, and some are desktop (not web, installed desk top).
Naturally, you can also develop more than one presentation tier.  For example, most likely you’ll choose to use one approach for mobile and a different library for web and tablet.  You can share a lot of client code between the two. I’ll be expanding on this topic in a future post.
Know what you Know
Styling and component libraries are big.  Consider drop downs, radio buttons, modals, tabs, inputs, date pickers, buttons, and on and on… Each library has a unique approach to each of the components.  It just takes a lot of time before fingers go auto-pilot and developers are not bogged down reading documentation and looking for examples.
This tends to drive devotion to one library or another.
When selecting a styling library, consider the team that will be implementing the presentation tier and what skills (and biases) they have.
Major Components
To increase your speed to market and manage costs, people are always looking for 3rd party components (commercial or open source) to give some nice short cuts.
Sometimes, you might find a perfect open source component, but it uses a different styling library. For example, if you committed to Angular Material, and then you find a Bootstrap module you want to use, you’re left in an awkward position.
Mixing CSS libraries can be treacherous and bloating, although the new view encapsulation may make this more feasible (but it won’t address bloat).  If the libraries must exist in a global space, then you risk name clashes.  If you can isolate them, then are they configurable enough to provide a seamless user experience?
Real Native vs. Hybrid vs. JavaScript Native
No discussion of presentation tier choices is complete without a discussion of real native apps. By “real” native, I mean using Java and Android Studio for Android and Objective C or Swift and XCode for iOS.
The question of using a hybrid vs. native for your mobile strategy is very different if you already have a predictable and productive team pumping out native Android and iOS apps compared to starting from a blank slate.
Native developers will likely be resistant to hybrid, and if it ain’t broke, don’t fix it (it being your team’s productivity).
However, a pattern I’ve seen at many start-ups is that they have squeaked out an iOS MVP and Android is constantly being pushed back.  Having made the native choice, the team rationally decides to get the iOS app more mature before investing in Android.  Weeks, turn to months, months turn to quarters, quarters turn to years.  No Android.
But don’t think hybrid is all roses.  Be prepared for the write-once, debug everywhere syndrome. When you’re staring at a white-screen-of-death or head banging some bizarre iOS only bug and the hours are ticking by, you’ll be cursing the hybrid choice wondering how much time you’re really saving.
Now that Angular supports native renderers with tools like NativeScript and React Native, a new middle ground opens up that offers some advantages:
Use the same client-side business logic implementation in your web, native Android, native iOS and desktop apps
Use JavaScript to develop “native” apps (consolidating the languages your team needs to know by focusing on TypeScript)
Develop a true native experience
A key question to consider is, “how much to invest in a native user experience for the next release?”.
iPhone users want their apps to look like iPhone apps and Android users want their apps to look like Android apps, or so the argument goes. On the other hand, my Gmail app on iPhone looks rather Material Design-ish and it doesn’t bother me.
How important is it for you to follow iPhone idioms, and to what degree? Should it just look good and be obvious how to use?  To whom? How does that translate to your specific app features? What do you want to be consistent across devices?
Browser based hybrid apps tend to be a less snappy than their native counter parts and native apps can more easily access features such as keyboard control and pull to refresh.
How much extra time are you willing to commit your team to, to build functionality unique to each device and honing the user experience? Do you want to economize and define the layout just once in your early iterations? Is hybrid performance good enough? Can you damage your brand with an early release that makes too many compromises? What data do you have from your customer discovery efforts to inform this decision?
Minimalist vs. Broad Feature Set
Since, this post was first written, I’ve added Basecss and Tachyons to the list of considerations.  Both prefer performance, elegance and smallness compared to large feature sets with Basecss being the leaner of the two.  Neither have any particular features for Angular 2.
Discussion of the Choices
OK, enough naval gazing.  What library should you use?  I’ll walk through some choices and add my perspectives.  I only have hands on experience with a few, and it is a rapidly evolving space, so comments are much appreciated and I’ll try to keep the post up-to-date.
Angular Material 2
Synopsis: CSS and directives following material design principals for mobile and web
Link: 
Release Stage: 2.0.0 Alpha (as of November, 2016)
Likes:
Automates the implementation of material design principles () which are very well accepted.




Simple clean looking HTML markup with good responsive features to allow you to automatically adjust to different screen sizes
It’s being made by Google who are hinting at an ambitious road map ()
With the development of progressive web apps () and increasingly capable browsers, you get a glimpse of a mobile future …

attachments.title: Galvanize Mentor Hours with Eric Kirby of Oracle
attachments.text: Gain more knowledge through Galvanize Mentor Hours with Eric Kirby:  Expertise: Start-ups, Data & Analytics, AdTech and Marketing Tech Industry Background:  Eric is responsible for all aspects of product delivery for the Oracle Data Cloud including Product Management, Development, Data Science, and Operations. He joined Oracle through the acquisition of Datalogix in 2015 where we served as Chief Operating Officer and earlier as Chief Product Officer. Previously Eric was the founder and CEO of Connection Engine, the customer intelligence and targeting platform acquired by Datalogix in 2012. Eric has also served as SVP & GM of Interactive Solutions at Merkle, one of the nation’s largest and fastest growing customer relationship marketing agencies, where he was responsible for developing digital media offerings including email, mobile, display, and social marketing solutions. Before Merkle, Eric was SVP & GM at DoubleClick where he led the Email Solutions division, the world’s largest email service provider at the time. An experienced entrepreneur, Eric previously co-founded two digital technology firms — Veripost and Assurance Systems — both were acquired by Return Path. Earlier he was Vice President of Interactive Services at Brierley & Partners, a leading loyalty marketing agency. Eric holds a BS in Industrial Engineering from Northwestern University and an MBA from Harvard Business School. About Galvanize Mentor Hours Exclusively for Galvanize members: Mentor Hours gives entrepreneurs and technologists the opportunity to engage with industry experts and entrepreneurs on topics ranging from fundraising, sales, marketing, product, legal, finance, and more. Members bring 1-3 challenges or specific questions and get practical, hands-on advice. Failure to attend mentor sessions will be tracked and a strike policy is applied.

attachments.title: Galvanize Mentor Hours with John Weiss of Human Design
attachments.text: Gain more knowledge through Galvanize Mentor Hours with John Weiss,  Expertise: Teach Startups UX/UI (been doing UX for 16yrs), How to Effectively Work Within a Small or Large Team Environment, How to Shape and Build a Holistic Experience From Concept to Code. Background: John's passion is Human Centered Design and creating experiences that are inherently human. John’s work is guided by purpose, passion, simplicity, beauty, innovation and surprise. With over sixteen years experience in interactive and experience design, John has built and led high performing design teams as the Executive Creative Director at WebMD, Director, Experience Design at Waggener Edstrom and Experience Director at Ascentium. Experiences that create lasting relationships and shape the future. attachments.title: Workshop: Elements of UX Design For Mobile Apps
attachments.text: About this workshop: User experience design is an integral component to the success of any early stage startup, playing a part in the early stages of achieving product-market fit, to high user growth, to lowering user acquisition costs.   When it comes to good design for mobile and web applications, one must consider what common attributes are shared amongst large app companies such as Facebook and Instagram. Just as each human being is composed of the same chemical elements, every good application contains the same user experience elements.   This workshop will review the 8 main elements for a good user experience. • Simplicity • OnBoarding • Focus • Engagement • Flow • Virality • Gamification • Delight   Each core element will be reviewed in-depth, providing real examples and illustrations to better understand their use and application. You’ll Learn How To: Apply design elements modeled from the greatest apps. Have a greater sense of what “user experience” means. Use industry best practices for mobile app design. Target Audience Tech founders who want to improve their mobile app. Mobile and web designers looking for new ways to build their skills. People who want to start their own mobile app, but don’t know where to start. Product managers who want a way to determine new features for their company. Developers who want to build awareness of what’s involved in the UX and visual design process. Meet Your Instructor: Pek Pongpaet is the Managing Partner at Silicon Valley based Impekable, a full service design and development studio with over 30 employees spanning six countries. Impekable crafts outstanding mobile and web products for clients that include Google, HP, Motorola, Twilio and Groupon, to name a few. His energetic and straightforward delivery puts theories about design and development into practice for mobile and web apps across all industries. Pek studied computer engineering at the University of Illinois at Chicago, but made a mid-career transition to design. Impekable website Pictacular received accolades from Time Magazine as one of the top 50 websites of 2013. In addition to mentoring startups and new designers at 500 Startups, Hackers / Founders, and Founders Floor Startup Accelerator, Pek’s also a ninja - literally.  He was a motion capture actor for Mortal Kombat games and has taught martial arts.

attachments.text: Early Adopter Pricing ends February 1! Galvanize Members: $165 (normally $180) Galvanize Students: $150 (normally $165 ) General Public: $200 (normally $225)   Make 2017 the year of learning Mobile Development - and get started with this practical two-day workshop at the Galvanize Boulder campus. Get your hands dirty with this intro 2-day class to Apple’s fast & intuitive language, Swift, which creates a seamless experience for app developers. At our workshop, students will learn the basics of Swift and Xcode and put those skills into practice by building two apps in two days.  This class is great for web developers or those who have a bit of coding experience, but beginning programmers will find value, too - although they may not complete the 2nd app.       HERE'S WHAT YOU WILL LEARN: • Using Xcode IDE and Interface Builder • Model-View-Controller design pattern • Basic UIKit components • IBOutlets and IBActions • UIViews and UIViewControllers • Data models • Deploying to devise • NSURLSession • Basic Swift syntax • Basic comp sci topics • Multiple views • UI Controls • Networking and APIs • Networking • Concurrency • JSON

For some reason, the github CLI will randomly start asking for your passphrase every time you attempt to push changes. If this happens to you, here is how to fix it WITHOUT needing to generate a brand new SSH key:
*Step 1*
On GitHub, click your avatar in the upper right. Go to Settings > SSH and GPG keys
*Step 2*
Delete your existing SSH key. _A warning will pop up, proceed with the deletion. It may be scary, but it’s going to be okay! I promise._
*Step 3*
Enter the following command in terminal:
`pbcopy < ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub`
_This copies your existing SSH key to clipboard._
*Step 4*
In your GitHub SSH settings, click ‘New SSH key’. An input box will appear on the page. 
In title, enter whatever you called it before. 
In key, cmd-v to paste the key you grabbed from the command line in the previous step.
Click ‘Add SSH key’ and you’re done! No more typing your passphrase every time you want to push to GitHub! YAAAY!!!

attachments.title: Google open-sources Chrome for iOS
attachments.text:
Google today announced that the code for Chrome for iOS is now part of its Chromium open source project.
On iOS, Chrome has to use Apple’s WebKit rendering engine instead of Google’s own Blink engine. Because of this, Google didn’t add the Chrome for iOS code to the Chromium code base before. Supporting both rendering engines in the same code base, after all, adds quite a bit of complexity.
Over the last few years, though, Google’s team worked on making the necessary code changes to add the Chrome for iOS code to Chromium. That work is now complete and developers who want to compile the iOS version of Chromium can now take the iOS code from the Chromium repository and do so (assuming, of course, that they run OS X and use Xcode).
Google argues that this move also means that the development speed for Chrome for iOS will now be faster, thanks to the fact that all of the tests the team runs on Chromium can now also automatically run on the Chrome for iOS code base, too.

<!here|@here> - Good reminder for everyone to keep in mind as you are working on your stories: make sure the stories are granular. They should be stories that are small enough that they can be completed and tested in an hour (or a few hours *max*). There shouldn’t be a single story that would take someone all day to complete. I realize that this can be hard to estimate, especially since you are using unfamiliar technologies, but the spirit of this is to make your stories small enough so anyone can pick it up and start working on it and if someone were to get stuck, it would be a small piece of the puzzle that they are stuck on.

messages.text:
<!group>. Graduation is in 8 weeks! Let’s keep your javascript skills sharp and work on leveling you up every day until then! These koans are about reading javascript and being able to discern expectations.

Fork and clone this repo: <https://github.com/mrdavidlaing/javascript-koans>
Work through *About Expects* and *About Arrays*. As you’re working through them I want you to be self-aware of the following:
* Did the setup instructions confuse you? How did you go about figuring it out? What things did you try? How long did it take you to ask for help?
* For the About Expects - this is a tutorial of sorts. It is giving you some guidance about how the tests work. Read the tests critically. What are they testing for? What are the expectations?
* For the About Arrays - Read the tests critically. If you were writing the test, what would you expect the output to be? This is what you will put in the FILL_ME_IN spot. `expect(typeof(emptyArray)).toBe(FILL_ME_IN);`
* Run the tests. At some point you may realize that you know what the expected answer is because of the pattern of the tests…make sure you know _why_ these are the expected answers. Take note of the ones that you got right, but didn’t understand why. Ask for reviews!

Thoughts on the New Technology requirement:

There have been some questions on what constitutes a significant new technology … here are my thoughts.

1.  Significant means that it must be integral to the project.  A fundamental part of its architecture and the success of the project is dependent on it.  
2. The main purpose of the project is not just to learn something new, but to take a chance and dive into the deep end with some new tech.
3. I know the impulse can be to take something you know - the CRUD app, and add some new library/api/etc on top of it.  Think beyond that - this is a chance to really do something differrent.
4. Taking a big chance will help your capstone.  You will not only have some experience planning with a new technology, but you will think outside the normal CRUD box - hopefully making for a varied and interesting group of capstones.

That being said … if you have an idea that is so good and exciting bring it to us.  We make exceptions for exceptional ideas.

If you are still stuck - look at the examples and choose one that seems interesting.

Please contact any of us with questions.  Thanks.

attachments.title: Diversity in Tech Career Day!
attachments.text: Everyone is welcome to attend this event without regard to race, color, religion, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, national origin, disability or veteran status. The event is simply structured around celebrating and supporting gender diversity in the tech realm. This event kicks off the launch of Flock, supporting women in tech in achieving their career dreams, with a give-first event for the community! Please join Girl Develop It, Women Who Code, local Meetup groups, students, and other tech-industry community members to meet with companies looking to fill software and engineering positions. We want to prioritize human-to-human interaction over paperwork -- You'll sit down at a table and talk with team members from real companies in the Denver/Boulder area. We'll get to know each other as humans rather than just a resume. This event is all the benefits of a job fair without the pointy elbows. If you're not currently looking for a job or just want to come support the community, you're still welcome! We'll have food and plenty of open space to roam around and have great conversations.WHAT SHOULD I BRING? Bring yourself and a positive attitude! You can bring your resume, but it's not necessary. You should also come hungry - because there's free food!FOOD AND DRINK Food will be provided and beverages will be purchasable at the Galvanize bar.WHAT COMPANIES ARE COMING? The list of currently attending companies is here! This will be updated periodically as we get closer to the event!YOU'RE CHARGING MONEY? Not for job seekers and community members -- that's free!We are charging companies who want to sponsor a table and talk to our magnificent attendees. 100% of the money will be donated to fund scholarships for Girl Develop It courses, Women Who Code and the Denver Scholarship Foundation.HOSTED BY: This event is hosted by a number of organizations who share a passion for diversity: ​Flock: A career accelerator for technical humans.Flock changes the reality of minorities and women in tech. We'll supplement our client's teams with talented full-time gender-diverse contractors, but also provide them with extensive ongoing support. Each member of the 'flock' will not only accelerate their tech skills, but also become a self-confident leader for others. The companies we work with build stronger products through greater diversity of perspective.Girl Develop It: Providing affordable programs for adult women interested in learning web and software development in a judgment-free environment.Girl Develop It is a nonprofit organization that exists to provide affordable and judgment-free opportunities for women interested in learning web and software development. Through in-person classes and community support, Girl Develop It helps women of diverse backgrounds achieve their technology goals and build confidence in their careers and their every day lives.Boulder JavaScript Meetup: A group focused specifically on the language that you and I both love, JavaScript. We're a friendly group and we welcome developers of all skill levels, beginner to expert. We want to foster an environment where it's okay to ask questions and it's okay not to know about certain aspects of the language. We're willing to share what we know, and are open to learning from others.Denver Scholarship Foundation: Making college possible for thousands of students in our community. For many students in Denver, continuing their education beyond high school doesn't seem like a viable option. Most often, it's not low grades or lack of extracurricular activities keeping them from pursuing their dreams. There are thousands of intelligent, hard-working individuals facing the most intimidating barrier to college of all -- they think it just isn't possible. But the Denver Scholarship Foundation is changing that. We're making a postsecondary degree possible for Denver's students. Our unique, three-part program for college success has been nationally recognized for its effectiveness. Dialog Lab: We start conversations that fuel your business.Whether 140 pages or 140 characters, a story well told leaves a lasting impression. From traditional media relations to interactive strategies, we know how to deliver your story. Our experienced team members specialize in every facet of the communications industry. We've embraced the changing media landscape and excel at helping companies like yours fuel the hype. Flatirons LGBTQ Tech: LGBTQ tech meetup based in Boulder, CO. The goals for creating this meetup are: community building, service work, and professional networking/socializing for LGBTQ folks and allies in the tech/startup space in Boulder. As of September 2014, we are an official National Center for Women & Information Technology (NCWIT) Affinity Group member.Galvanize: Where learning goes to work. We believe in making education and growth accessible to anyone – especially underrepresented groups in the tech industry. Whether you’re a founder, student, or just someone who wants to level up their career, we want Galvanize to be a welcoming, inclusive place where you can take the next step in your journey.MergeLane: Discovering, accelerating and investing in exceptional women and the companies they run.MergeLane is broadening the onramp for women at key stages of the startup and innovation ecosystem. MergeLane accelerates high-potential female leaders and startups with at least one female in leadership. The  platform currently comprises four main pillars: The MergeLane Accelerator, Leadership Camp, MergeLane Fund, and High-Quality Content. Women In Machine Learning and Data Science: We aim to provide an inviting and educational community for women interested in data.We host events which include talks by prominent data scientists, lightning talks, technical workshops and networking events. Our members include engineers, technologists, statisticians, students and many other professionals who work in data science or would like to transition into this field.Women Who Code: We support all women in their coding aspirations. Women Who code is a professional community for women in tech. We provide an avenue for women to pursue a career in technology, help them gain new skills and hone existing skills for professional advancement, and foster environments where networking and mentorship are valued. Whether you're a full-time programmer looking to expand your network and skills, or you have always wanted to give coding a try, you are welcome!Women Who Startup: Changing the face of entrepreneurship, together.Women Who Startup is dedicated to building a platform for women who are innovators, technologists, entrepreneurs, developers, educators, community members and more, with community, a powerful network and resources to fuel your current or next innovation or entrepreneurial endeavor. Join us!Women Rising: A grassroots non-profit for women in tech and business to meet, connect and mentor each other. Talk to other women who are as dedicated to their careers as you are. We employ our proven algorithmic process to create "mini-meetup" groups of three that are selected by peer groups, industry, and city. If you have a specific question, you can also request a more experienced mentor to talk to. It's like online dating, but for women who influence your career. All attendees are expected to abide by the Girl Develop It Code of Conduct.

<!group> I wanted to drop a line and share a cool story about LinkedIn networking…a lady named Jess reached out to me from North Carolina about a month and a half ago expressing interest in a career services opportunity in Denver w/ Galvanize. I (admittedly) didnt get back to her after her first message, however she sent a follow up message a week later. After seeing her persistence, and actually taking a look at her LI page, we scheduled a phone call. She came prepared with a handful of questions and asked a lot about my job and Galvanize as a whole. She ended up interviewing for the position and started with our team this week!

TL;DR: Someone used LI to reach out, reached out again because I was unresponsive, got an interview and landed the job. It works, people!

For those of you who have been doing this already, keep it up! Your hard work will pay off. For those of you reluctant to start, please reach out directly and we can create a gameplan around how to do so!

I made this little process list for Pestridge last night; but anyone is free to use it to study real fast:

1. Map out the idea I want to do, it should just be a single database/schema that supports C(reate)R(ead)U(pdate)D(estroy). In my circumstance, I will probably be doing a books database. 
2. I would create my file structure:
   - Create my folder, immediately type in `git init`. 
   - Then I would create my server file, using `touch server.js`.
   - I'd also create my public folder which would store my HTML. 
        - I would store my index.html folder using `touch index.html`. 
        - I would create css and js folders in the public folder for the future.
2. I would then type in `npm init` to initialize my node package.json manager. 
   - I would then install my dependencies, the things I know I will use; for this:
        - `body-parser`, `knex`, `pg`, `express`. 
3. After doing that, I would create my knexfile.js using `knex init`. 
   - Then I would start by creating my migration file: `knex migrate:make _`.
   - I'd probably do the same thing for seeds, and make sure they both are fine. 
   - I can't forget to make a database, otherwise I'd hit errors; so `createdb`. 
4. Then, I would start building the initial app inside of server.js; just get it online. 
         - Call in my dependencies, things like express, knex, etc. 
         - Then, make my public middleware: `app.use(express.static('public'));`
         - Finally, make a listener for my port handling using `app.listen(PORT)`.
5. After that, I'd go back up halfway through the document and make my route. 
6. Also make my routes folder on the same level as my server.js file. 
7. Then in my route, make sure it's running. Getting back a simple /GET request. 
8. After that, I'd make my POST/PATCH/DELETE using the ID column of my db. You should have `/:id` in most of your things, besides POST/GET (not GET/:id).

*Heroku Deployment List:*

After you download it; go and sign up on Heroku's website so you get a user login so that you can use your CLI, after that, here's your heroku workflow, INSIDE of your folder that holds your CRUD app, and your CRUD app MUST be a git:

`heroku` (this will sign you in on CLI)
`heroku create PROJECT_NAME`
`heroku addons:create heroku-postgresql` (Adds the pSQL server). 
in your knexfile.js; enter in this for production:
`process.env.DATABASE_URL` (WITHOUT quotes around it). 
Then when you're done with all of that, just make sure you do the following things to your package.json file so it knows what to do:
    - Add in a "node server.js" line instead of "nodemon server.js". That's basically it. 
Then, in your master branch of your CRUD app, make sure you're up to date, and then use the command `git push heroku master` to push your current repo onto heroku. 
Then run:
    - `heroku run knex migrate:latest` && `heroku run knex seed:run`. 
And poof, you're deployed to Heroku.

I thought I'd share some job search/networking tips I received from a g4 grad who secured a job before graduating:
• Instead of trying to go to all things, focus on a few meet ups and try to attend those few consistently. Meet ups usually have a core group of members who show up every time. This allows you to build a stronger rapport with those people and they are more likely to seek you out when there is an opening at their company. 
• Pick 10-12 companies hiring on Glass Door or Built in Colorado, then really study the job listings. Look for commonalities in skills/technologies/experiences being sought and be mindful of your mastery of those things as the course progresses

attachments.title: What interns and new grads really get paid at top tech companies
attachments.text:
From woefully underpaid internships to legendary hiring bonuses at huge Silicon Valley companies, it’s hard for job seekers to know what they’re worth in tech. It’s even harder when they’re new to the rat race.
One undergraduate computer science student at Purdue University, Jesse Collins, has taken it upon himself to gather data from undergrads and recent grads to find out what’s going on, for real, around job offers and paid internships today in tech.
Collins released the preliminary results of his survey this week, in a Google spreadsheet here, and the study is already full of juicy tidbits.
For example, Collins found that, according to 19 survey respondents so far, Facebook is offering an average annual salary of $109,526 with a massive signing bonus of $79,737 for employees in technical roles like iOS or full stack developer, or software or network engineer.
By comparison, according to 31 survey respondents, Google is paying recent graduates in tech roles an average of $107,000 annualized salary with an average signing bonus of $27,327.
And Microsoft was offering new grads a $107,455 annualized salary with a $26,591 signing bonus, according to 22 respondents.


New Grad and Intern tech offers for 2017 💰💰💰 #SiliconValley Data here:  
— Jesse Collins (@jtc_au) December 2, 2016

Looking at the self-reported salary and bonus data by job title, Collins found that software engineers and developers are out-earning their peers in user experience design and sales engineering by tens of thousands, annually.
And even though government salaries are presumed to be much lower than those in the private sector, working in tech in a government office will score entry-level engineers and developers a slightly better salary, on average, than working for a seed- or Series A-stage startup, the survey suggests.
It’s important to note that some large tech employers, including Facebook and Google, offer internships to both graduate and undergraduate students, and may be hiring people with doctorates and prior work experience into entry-level roles. That could account for some of those high salary and internship compensation numbers.
Collins began his survey last year, asking recent tech hires and interns what offers they got and from which companies, as well as for a bit of personal information, including their educational background and gender.
He says, “I’m interested in bringing transparency to job searches and salary negotiations overall, and hope that the data…will help prevent racial bias, a gender wage gap and the like.”
Preliminary survey results show that women who are recent grads may be getting paid more on average than their male peers in entry-level tech roles. Women say they are getting $105,000 to $142,674 annualized salary on average, while men are saying they are getting an average annualized salary between $99,767 and $105,000.
However, the same survey suggests that women are paid less, right after college, than men, at Facebook, Google and Twitter, taking stock, stipends, hiring bonuses and annual salaries all into account.
And women are not getting hired as often as men, the survey also reflects, comprising just 14 percent of new grad tech hires who were gender-identified respondents.
Collins isn’t the first to try to understand who gets paid for what in tech.
Other noteworthy researchers include Harvard economics professor Claudia Goldin, 20-something software engineer Rodney Folz, who began his own internship-focused survey as an undergrad at U.C. Berkeley, and companies that get paid by recruiters and job seekers, like LinkedIn, CareerBuilder or Glassdoor.
A self-proclaimed machine learning and stats nerd, Collins cautioned readers of his spreadsheet that survey results are not final, and the data set he’s gathered is not big enough to draw broad conclusions about pay, or bias in tech.
The information is self-reported and salaries were not adjusted for cost of living by region. And he hasn’t connected with companies to verify the data.
The survey, 2016 New Grad & Internship Offer Data, is still open if you’re a recent graduate or undergrad who wants to contribute internship or job offer data.
TechCrunch has reached out to a number of employers in the survey to verify the salary and other information reflected there. We will update this post if or when we have new information. Facebook does not comment on its employees’ compensation, a company spokesperson said.
Meanwhile, Collins has accepted a full-time job as a software engineer at the Seattle office of Curalate after he graduates from Purdue. He declined to disclose his salary in a press interview.

*Standard:Build a CRUD app with a single resource*-
Includes migrations
Includes seeds
Is completed in under 3 hours
Lists all records with GET /things
Creates a record with POST /things
Shows new form with /things/new
Shows one record with GET /things/:id
Shows an edit form with GET /things/:id/edit (form fields are pre-filled)
Updates a record with POST /things/:id
Deletes a record with POST /things/:id/delete
Redirects on create / update / delete
All code can be in one controller/routes file
Project structure can be generated by a generator such as the Express Generator or Yeoman, but the CRUD code must be original
Form labels must connect properly to form controls (via the for attribute, even when nesting)

messages.text:
TIP: Postgres keeps track of the sequences for any of the incrementing serial id columns in its tables. Doing a describe on a table will show the name of the sequence it is using in the modifiers column. When data is inserted with the id hardcoded, which is often desirable with test data, the sequence will not be aware of this. So, it's important to advance the sequence to the last id. An example alter statement to do this would be:

```
knex.raw("SELECT setval('books_id_seq', (SELECT MAX(id) FROM books))")
```

GitHub – Master/Feature Branch Workflow

1.	Create Master GitHub – This is for the group to work on. Add permissions to collaborators so they can create feature branches.
2.	Git Clone Repo – clone the repo on your computer
3.	Create Feature Branch on GitHub - for new feature.
4.	Git pull origin master – This gets your local machine up to date with any changes done in GitHub on master including new feature branch.
5.	Git checkout branchname – This moves you into the new branch to work on.
6.	Work On Your Feature
7.	Git add – Add your changes to git
8.	Git Commit – commit your changes to your local branch
9.	Git pull origin master – This makes sure everything is current on your local machine
10.	Resolve Merge Conflicts – resolving merge conflicts from the feature branch
11.	Git push origin branchname – this pushes your change to the GitHub branch.
12.	On GitHub - Create new pull request – Compare and Pull (look at the changes, look for any conflicts, etc.)
13.	Make sure “Able To Merge” –on GitHub
14.	Create Pull Request – on GitHub
15.	Check for Changes – review changes, teammates can review and approve
16.	Merge Pull Request – Now Master is up to date.
17.	Move to new branch – git checkout master or get checkout newbranch – make sure you’re working on the right branch – git pull origin master to make sure you’re still up to date.

After talking with a number of students, it seems that many of you would like more time to work on the Apartment Lab assignment before doing a review. Let’s postpone the afternoon recap and spend the time working individually on the assignment. We can schedule a review session at a later time.

I will do a check for understanding for these objectives before we get going in the morning:
- Explain what an entity relationship diagram is.
- Explain why an entity relationship diagram is useful.
- Explain what PostgreSQL column constraints are.
- Explain what a join clause is.
- Explain why a join clause is useful.

<!group>: Your prep for tomorrow is to review this article - <https://learn.galvanize.com/content/gSchool/sql-curriculum/master/Entity%20Relationship%20Diagrams.md>

Node Package Manager Objectives - 
You will be able to:

- Explain the purpose of NPM
- Install a global module (npm -g <module>)
- Initialize NPM (npm init)
- Install a package using NPM (npm <module> --save)
- Explain the purpose of the package.json file
- Explain Semver (semantic versioning)

attachments.title: LastPass on mobile is now free
attachments.text:
LastPass, the password manager owned by LogMeIn, is making a core component of its service free.
LastPass helps improve password security by allowing users to generate random passwords and storing them securely, so users don’t have to worry about password reuse leading to one of their accounts being breached.
The company’s payment model has always been sort of frustrating — users could access the the browser extension for free but had to pay a $12 annual fee to take their passwords with them on mobile. Other password managers such as 1Password follow a similar pay-for-mobile model, but making the same service cost a different amount depending on what device it’s accessed from seemed nonsensical.
LastPass has added other paid features over the years that make the Premium subscription worthwhile, and under the new plan, the division between paid and free services makes a lot more sense. LastPass Premium users will still pay a subscription to access family password sharing, two-factor authentication methods like YubiKey and Sesame, encrypted file storage, fingerprint identification on desktop, priority customer support and an ad-free password vault. Free services will now include two-factor authentication, password generation and sync, and access from unlimited devices.
Basically, LastPass is now charging only for enhanced features rather than convenient access. The company also earns revenue from its enterprise offerings.
LastPass says that the change is motivated by a commitment to bringing password security to the masses. “Today’s reality is that people’s digital lives are increasingly in the cloud — and inherently span countless personal and work devices. We believe that to truly benefit from the security and convenience of a password manager, it should be available whenever and wherever you need it,” LastPass vice president Joe Siegrist said in a statement. “By offering LastPass for free across all your devices, we’re making it that much easier for everyone to make good password habits the norm, while resetting the expectations of what a great password management experience should be in a multi-device world.” 
	Related Articles

					LogMeIn Acquires Password Management Software LastPass For $110 Million
					LastPass Finds Security Holes In Its Online Password Manager, Doesn't Think Anyone Exploited Them
					Following Numerous Data Breaches, Dashlane And LastPass Apps Can Now Reset Passwords For You
					LastPass Launches A Native Password Manager For Mac Offering Quick Search, Security Checks And Offline Access
	
But the pricing change might also be intended to lure users from other paid password management services. LogMeIn CEO Bill Wagner said on an earnings call last week that free users drive revenue for LastPass because they often convert to Premium services or serve as referrals for enterprise business opportunities.
“LastPass is proving to be a great new on-ramp to the LogMeIn franchise, attracting millions of free users, many of whom will either upgrade to a paid account or lead us to an enterprise opportunity. And we saw this play out in the quarter with a six-figure deal to one of the nation’s largest commercial banks. We believe it is early days for cloud-based identity and that we have a big near-term opportunity to capture significant share by making LastPass even easier to use and increasing its awareness in the market,” Wagner explained.
Since LastPass was purchased by LogMeIn last year for $110 million, its rankings in the App Store and Google Play have remained virtually unchanged, according to the analyst service App Annie. Steady rankings are a good sign, and making the basics of LastPass available free of charge might help those rankings improve.
Users who are already paying for LastPass won’t have their subscriptions cancelled. Premium users get all the additional features, including YubiKey authentication and file storage, and LastPass doesn’t want to automatically cut people off from those tools. So to switch over to the Free model, users need to cancel their subscription when it comes up for renewal. Users who just signed up for Premium within the last 30 days are eligible for refunds.

Heeeyyyyyyy <!channel>… PLEASE READ:
 
I had some disappointing news this afternoon after both Galvanize members, as well as Jorge and Norma (our wonderful facilities folks that are NOT our moms but take very good care of us anyway) reported to me that there were multiple students drunk, disorderly, riding bikes around downstairs in the membership area with beers in hand (seriously?!?!? this is not your frat house!!) and then leaving our campus with alcohol. Not only are NONE of these things ok, they are ALL in breech of the contracts that you signed with Galvanize, incredibly disrespectful to the benefits this campus provides, and **illegal** in regards to those that left the campus with booze. While it is up to Galvanize to ensure that the kegs are de-tapped at the end of the day, it is an expectation of the entire community to respect the environment, our property, and to act professionally at all times.

This is a warning that I am giving to both cohorts. Please don’t make me come in and lecture you on my favorite topic of “How to Be an Adult”, and please don’t make me take further action. I don’t want to remove anyone from the program for making a poor decision, and I also don’t want to punish the entire campus by taking away the beer because students can't handle it. 

Sorry to wrap up the Friday with a warning, but it’s important to note that this won’t be tolerated. Please respond with an emoji so that I know this has been read and understood. kthanks.

<@U2AT5RLH2>: I  think I  can explain the nuance of this better in person... but you don’t have to define a key because they are part of the definition of an Object. In order to assign key/value pairs to an Object there has to be one…meaning you have to explicitly create the Object. Using the object literal syntax `{}` is like writing `new Object()`- in both cases an Object is created and linked to the Object prototype. attachments.title: JavaScript Array: slice vs splice
attachments.text: In JavaScript, mistaking slice for splice (or vice versa) is a common mistake among rookies and even experts. These two functions, although they have similar names, are doing two completely different things. In practice, such a confusion can be avoided by choosing an API that telegraphs the const-correctness of the function.

_Hey Galvanizers,_

_I’m writing to share some exciting news about the way we do things here at Galvanize._

_As you know already, we are committed to providing our students the opportunity to master the most current tech skills they will need to succeed in their careers. We remain very proud of our programs and the outstanding successes of our graduates._

_Our focus on our education mission includes helping our current and future students make smart financial decisions about their educations and careers. Where and how students choose to invest in their education is one of the most important decisions of their lives._

_To help our students and all education consumers make better choices, we’ve initiated a new standard – the Galvanize Standard – of transparency and independent verification of our job placement and salary data and made that information available to the public on our website._

_We’re not stopping there. We have invested in further training for our admissions counselors to ensure that that our prospective students get accurate information about our programs and credits; we will continue to prioritize hiring and recruiting qualified instructors; and we will continue to partner with lending institutions that share our values._

_You can read about the new Galvanize Standard on our blog:_ <http://www.galvanize.com/galvanize-standard/>

_I am proud and grateful for everything each of you do every day to make Galvanize and our learn community amazing. Thank you!_

_Chief Galvanizer, Jim_

messages.text: Write a letter to yourself - Come back to this letter when you need encouragement. Whatever you think you'll be bad at during this course, mention it. If you're bad at getting to bed on time and waking up in the morning, then encourage yourself to take your sleep hygiene seriously. If you're bad at hitting the books when you get home, tell yourself how important it is to you that you focus. If you're scared you won't understand and are doing a bad job, remind yourself that this is hard, you will struggle, but that you know you can do it if you spend enough time on it. If you're bad at asking for help, remind yourself that you're a learner, and it's acceptable to need support when you're learning. Write down what you will have wanted to do, so that your future self can live up to your expectations.

Write a letter to your friends & family - explain that you need to spend as much time as possible programming and working to change your life. If they want to support you, the best way they can do that is by helping you spend as much time as possible on this. Maybe that means releasing you from some obligations for awhile. Maybe that means helping you get your laundry done, or making sure you go to bed at a reasonable time. Your time is at an extreme premium right now! Explain that you might be a bad friend for awhile, but that you need their help to succeed.

attachments.title: Web Audio API
attachments.text: The Web Audio API involves handling audio operations inside an audio context, and has been designed to allow modular routing. Basic audio operations are performed with audio nodes, which are linked together to form an audio routing graph. Several sources — with different types of channel layout — are supported even within a single context. This modular design provides the flexibility to create complex audio functions with dynamic effects.

Knowing that I can always better myself. This course obviously provides new technical skills, but also a strong work ethic and a healthy mindset towards learning.
<https://learn.galvanize.com/content/gSchool/productivity-curriculum/master/Development%20Environment/README.md>
<!here|@here>: <https://github.com/gSchool/productivity-curriculum/tree/master/Development%20Environment>

A balanced life, between work and personal life. I want to enjoy my work and be proud of what I'm doing but also I want to have time and financial flexibility to enjoy my personal life, help my dreams come true etc. I know that if I'll work hard I'll get better, I'll get an awesome job that I like and that gave me some kind of life security and flexibility.....
One of my core values is continuing to challenge myself and build upon past success.    Web developing is never a done deal and there is always more to learn.

Core value: Respecting privacy. Web development is a field that potentially offers all people a path towards greater autonomy and safety in an ever expanding digital world. I relish the opportunity to work in computer security and add to the knowledge base of the community, working against common threats.
One of my core values is motivating myself and others when things get tough. As a web developer, I will use this value when I am feeling stuck and will help others when they are feeling stuck.

Core Value: Reliability. It’s incredibly important to me that my friends, family, and classmates feel that they can rely on me for some of their needs. Reliability in code is equally important. A build that doesn’t run or doesn’t do what it should is unreliable. A build that doesn’t fill the user’s need is unacceptable.
My core value is authenticity - Creating work (or a work ethic) that reflects your personal morals or experience whenever possible.

Examining Practices. I am inherently lazy and thus try to find the most efficient ways of doing things. As long as this doesn't come at the expense of quality it is very beneficial for web developers to be efficient and constantly search for newer, better ways of doing things.

Core value: Constantly search for solutions
Web dev contributes to my value in two ways.  It puts me in an environment where I am constantly problem solving and searching for solutions to tasks assigned by Galvanize.  It also provides me tools and even shows me how to create my own tools to assist me in my various searches for solutions
Lots of good insight, everyone! Thank you for sharing!

One of my core values is perseverance. Web development relates to this value because there are always problems that arise while coding and it takes a lot of effort to dedicate yourself to solving them.
I have two core values that go together - equality and hard work - with web development everyone has an equal opportunity to learn and be successful based on how much work put into learning.

My core value is that happiness is the meaning of life; that a life without happiness is pointless. That in mind, I always knew that whatever career path I chose needed to be based in something I am passionate about. I need to enjoy my work. I also strongly believe that work-life balance is a necessity for happiness. Web development will provide both a career that I enjoy and the financial freedom to pursue my other passions (and for my husband to pursue his passions).

Equal Opportunity - Regardless of age, race or socioeconomic background everyone should have the opportunity to work hard. Open access to information can create new opportunities. As web developers, we can reach diverse audiences that might benefit from the information we share.

One of my core values is constantly to evolve and adapt to new things. I want to continue to learn and grow as I age. Ideally i want to be a perpetual student and turn it into a career. In the past all my jobs have become mundane and boring and my mind stopped growing and became stagnate.  Getting into and completing this program will allow me to learn new things and continue to evolve and grow as a person.

Core value: self-improvement
		- By collaborating with other programmers, I can share what I've learned with others, and learn new ideas that I haven't thought of; not just for coding langauages/concepts, but for stress mitigation, project planning/management, and overall success stategies.

Core value is motivation. When you come into work each day you need to be motivated by what you are doing (as opposed to being motivated by fear of losing the job or anger at management). Web development focuses on a skillset and a problem-solving environment that is fulfilling above and beyond the monetary compensation.
Core Value: Creativity. Web Development is the easiest, cheapest and most effective way of being Creative nowadays.. nothing can beat it

One of my core values is the pursuit of the beautiful. Web development can be used in service of this pursuit through both the creation of elegant code & interfaces and the deeper appreciation for the elegance of good applications written by others. Not to mention the power to hack into and fix (or reinvent in a more elegant way) that which is ugly.
One of my core values is the determination to solve problems, especially unexpected ones. This relates to code development of all types and is beneficial in finding solutions to code glitches.

I’m going with Creation. I’m finding that as I age I am most satisfied with actions that result in a clear object of my efforts. Articles I’ve written, drawings I’ve made, machines I’ve built bring me much more joy than things I have done, but leave no real trace. "There is now a thing that exists due solely to my actions.” This is a luxury that coding allows for me.

At the core, I value precision in detail, because the more precise I am, the less confusion is created for those around me, and because, as they say, "the devil is in the details," and I think we can all agree that it's the tiniest things, sometimes, that cause the biggest problems, often because they're the hardest to track down.

Helping people - In Web Development I feel as if you are one big team trying to make the internet a better place. I really like the concept of open-source and how people come together from all over to make one project better and better.

Never giving up is one of my core values. Life=struggle, and if you can’t find the joy in the pain, or at least the purpose, then it all becomes arbitrary. Programming is an analogy for life. Also, never letting creativity die! Programming === creating
One of my core values is to be of service.  Through web development I can help create technology in the forms of apps or websites that promote social justice.
one of my core values is positivity.  encouraging each other and creating an environment that supports problem solving through positive feedback and collaboration

Integrity - always doing your best, even when no one is watching! You must always be managing your time and brand as a Web Developer - and strive to always be the best you can be as that is what will set you apart.

One of my core values is keeping an honest and dedicated work ethic. In the Web Development field I feel it can directly relate and be used in service of by keeping myself focused on the work I am putting in and the work that will be coming our way. For example, being honest when I don’t quite understand something can lead to developing a better understanding with said issue, and having the work ethic and drive to back it up will take me far.

One of my core values is just working hard, persevering through problems and struggles, and finding solutions regardless of the obstacles. Web-development and development in general both require perseverance and dedication, and that is why it has always interested me.
Helping people - Building apps that can help people in their everyday lives and make it more enjoyable.

One of my core values is that hard work pays off. Web development is exactly that. If you don’t put in hard work, odds are what you create wont be that good. You have to give it a lot of effort to succeed.

One of my core values is a love of learning, being a lifelong learner. Web development completely fits with that because technology changes quickly; new languages come out frequently, so I’ll constantly be learning something new or learning how to improve my current skillset. That excites and energizes me. :slightly_smiling_face:

My main core value is to make people’s lives better.  Web development will help me make people’s lives better through the use of Webpages/Apps that fulfill different needs.  For example the application and website mint helps people to effectively manage their finances.

attachments.title: Learning How to Learn: Powerful mental tools to help you master tough subjects - University of California, San Diego | Coursera
attachments.text: Learning How to Learn: Powerful mental tools to help you master tough subjects from University of California, San Diego. This course gives you easy access to the invaluable learning techniques used by experts in art, music, literature, math, science, sports, and many other disciplines. We’ll learn about the how the brain uses two very different learning modes and how it encapsulates (“chunks”) information. We’ll also cover illusions of learning, memory techniques, dealing with procrastination, and best practices shown by research to be most effective in helping you master tough subjects. Using these approaches, no matter what your skill levels in topics you would like to master, you can change your thinking and change your life. If you’re already an expert, this peep under the mental hood will give you ideas for: turbocharging successful learning, including counter-intuitive test-taking tips and insights that will help you make the best use of your time on homework and problem sets. If you’re struggling, you’ll see a structured treasure trove of practical techniques that walk you through what you need to do to get on track. If you’ve ever wanted to become better at anything, this course will help serve as your guide. To join the fully translated Portuguese version of the course, visit: <https://www.coursera.org/learn/aprender> To join the fully translated Spanish version of the course, visit: <https://www.coursera.org/learn/aprendiendo-a-aprender> To join the fully translated Chinese version of the course, visit: <https://www.coursera.org/learn/ruhe-xuexi> 1000+ courses from schools like Stanford and Yale - no application required. attachments.title: How to Be More Productive - Freakonomics
attachments.text: It’s Self-Improvement Month at Freakonomics Radio. We begin with a topic that seems to be on everyone’s mind: how to get more done in less time. First, however, a warning: there’s a big difference between being busy and being productive.
attachments.fallback: Freakonomics: How to Be More Productive - Freakonomics

attachments.title: How to Become Great at Just About Anything - Freakonomics
attachments.text: What if the thing we call “talent” is grotesquely overrated? And what if deliberate practice is the secret to excellence? Those are the claims of the research psychologist Anders Ericsson, who has been studying the science of expertise for decades. He tells us everything he’s learned.
attachments.fallback: Freakonomics: How to Become Great at Just About Anything - Freakonomics

attachments.title: How to Get More Grit in Your Life - Freakonomics
attachments.text: The psychologist Angela Duckworth argues that a person’s level of stick-to-itiveness is directly related to their level of success. No big surprise there. But grit, she says, isn’t something you’re born with — it can be learned. Here’s how.
